{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2012}} {{Infobox top level domain |name=museum |background=#FCC |image=[[File:Dotmuseum.png|250px|.museum – The most interesting museums in the world. All connected in a single dot.]] |introduced=2001 |type=[[Sponsored top-level domain]] |status=Active |registry=[[Museum Domain Management Association]] |sponsor=[[Museum Domain Management Association]] (set up by [[International Council of Museums]]) |intendeduse=Museums |actualuse=Museums (though few use it as their primary advertised address) |restrictions=Credentials of applicants are checked before registration is permitted |structure=Registrations originally had to be at third or higher level beneath generic category, but later direct second-level registrations were allowed |document=[http://www.icann.org/tlds/agreements/museum/ ICANN registry agreement] |disputepolicy=[[UDRP]], [http://www.icann.org/tlds/agreements/sponsored/sponsorship-agmt-att12-13oct01.htm Charter Eligibility Dispute Resolution Procedure (CEDRP)] |website=[http://about.museum/ about.museum] |dnssec=yes}}
'''museum''' is a [[sponsored top-level domain]] (sTLD) in the [[Domain Name System]] of the Internet used exclusively by [[museum]]s, museum associations, and individual members of the museum profession, as these groups are defined by the [[International Council of Museums]] (ICOM).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.archimuse.com/mw2001/papers/hamma/hamma.html | title=A Top Level Museum Domain | publisher=[[Archives & Museum Informatics]] |work=MW2011: [[Museums and the Web]] | date=2001 |accessdate=20 July 2011 | author =Karp, Cary | author-link =Cary Karp | author2 =Hamma, Kenneth | last-author-amp =yes}}</ref>
In joint action with the [[J. Paul Getty Trust]], ICOM established the [[Museum Domain Management Association]] (MuseDoma), headed by [[Cary Karp]], for the purpose of submitting an application to [[ICANN]] for the creation of the new [[generic top-level domain]] (gTLD), and to operate a registry.<ref>[http://www.icann.org/tlds/agreements/museum/ The .museum Sponsorship Agreement], [[ICANN]].</ref> The {{mono|museum}} domain was entered into the [[DNS root]] on 20 October 2001, and was the first sponsored top-level domain to be instituted through ICANN's action.
The purpose of this domain is to reserve a segment of the DNS name space reserved for the use of museums; a name space whose conventions are defined by the museum community. The {{mono|museum}} TLD grants users a quick and intuitive way to verify the authenticity of a museum site. Conversely, since it is a type of formal third-party certification, museums using this name space obtain a way to assure visitors of the site's validity.
In addition to the eligibility requirements specified in the {{mono|museum}} charter, naming conventions apply to the labeling of subdomains. Extensive support is also being introduced for [[internationalized domain names]], as described at {{mono|about.museum}}.<ref>[http://about.museum/idn/ Internationalized domain names (IDNs) in .museum – Introduction] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110218013204/http://about.museum/idn/ |date=18 February 2011 }}, [http://about.museum/ about.museum].</ref>
Registration are processed via accredited registrars.<ref>[http://about.museum/registrars/ List of .museum accredited registrars] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051211121127/http://about.museum/registrars/ |date=11 December 2005 }}, about.museum.</ref>
