{{Infobox historic site | name = Cockpit | image = The_cockpit_at_St_Fagans_-_geograph.org.uk_-_631971.jpg | location = [[St Fagans National Museum of History]], [[Cardiff]] | coordinates = {{coord|51.4876|-3.27736|display=inline,title}} | built = Late 17th century | rebuilt = 1965 | designation1 = Grade II | designation1_offname = Denbigh Cockpit | designation1_date = 10 June 1977 | designation1_number = 13856<ref >{{cite web|url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/wa-13856-denbigh-cockpit-st-fagans|title=Denbigh Cockpit, St Fagans|work=British Listed Buildings|accessdate=15 November 2013}}</ref>}}
'''Denbigh Cockpit''' is a reconstructed building at [[St Fagans National Museum of History]] in [[Cardiff]], the capital of [[Wales]]. The [[cockpit (cockfighting)|cockpit]] formerly stood in the yard of the Hawk and Buckle Inn at Vale Street, [[Denbigh]], and is thought to date from the late seventeenth century.<ref >[http://www.peoplescollectionwales.co.uk/Item/60538-hawk-and-buckle-cockpit-denbigh People's Collection Wales: Hawk and Buckle cockpit, Denbigh]. Accessed 6 November 2013</ref> It is a Grade II listed building.
[[Cockfighting]] became illegal in Britain in 1849, and the cockpit was used for other purposes over the years, such as a garage. In 1911 it was visited by members of the Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments and Constructions in Wales and Monmouthshire, and was found to be "preserved with much care".<ref >[https://books.google.com/books?id=98kHnuPa-JIC&pg=PA46&lpg=PA46&dq=hawk+and+buckle+inn+cockpit&source=bl&ots=E5wV5uTcF0&sig=rARd36k7yaMbqVktlrvVWaZycSU&hl=en&sa=X&ei=xH96Us7FIseJ0AXSzIHQDA&ved=0CIgBEOgBMA0#v=onepage&q=hawk%20and%20buckle%20inn%20cockpit&f=false ''An Inventory of the Ancient Monuments in Wales and Monmouthshire'', 1911]. Accessed 6 November 2013</ref> It was in a poor state of repair by 1965, when a decision was made to move it to St Fagans.<ref >[http://www.museumwales.ac.uk/en/stfagans/buildings/cockpit/?display_mode=mobile Cockpit – National Museum Wales]. Accessed 6 November 2013</ref> The cockpit was opened to the public at St Fagans in 1970.
