{{Orphan|date=February 2009}}
'''John Does 1-570 v. George W. Bush''' is a combined writ of [[habeas corpus]] submitted on behalf of detainees held in [[extrajudicial detention]] in the [[United States]] [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp]]s, in [[Cuba]].<ref name=NationalReview2005-12-05> {{cite web |url = http://old.nationalreview.com/murdock/murdock200601250929.asp |title = Gitmo legal: why are top-notch law firms aiding Gitmo detainees? |publisher = [[National Review]] |author = [[Deroy Murdock]] |date = December 5, 2005 |accessdate = 2008-06-22 |quote = John Does 1-570 v. George W. Bush, which is essentially a class-action suit involving every enemy combatant at Gitmo not already suing the president for release during wartime. |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100501191406/http://old.nationalreview.com/murdock/murdock200601250929.asp |archivedate = May 1, 2010 |df = }} </ref>
== Background == Following the attacks of [[September 11th]], 2001, the [[United States]] began an offensive known as the [[War on Terror]]. A number of individuals suspected of terrorist ties or activities were held in Cuba at the [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp]]s.
== Description == Several hundred of the detainees in Guantanamo had individual [[habeas corpus]] petitions filed on their behalf. When the lawyers working on the captives' behalf encountered difficulties with the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] over the captives' names,<ref name=SetonHallSuicide> {{cite news | url=http://law.shu.edu/news/guantanamo_report_june_suicides_8_21_06.pdf#7 | title=June 10th Suicides at Guantánamo: Government Words and Deeds Compared | page=7 | publisher=[[Seton Hall University]] | author=[[Mark Denbeaux]]| date=August 21, 2006 | accessdate=2008-06-11 | quote=The Government then informed counsel in December that the detainee had been positively identified because the newer version of the name more closely matched a detainee. However, the Government refused to provide the detainee's identification ISN number and also refused to allow the lawyers to send a letter to their client until the attorneys displayed their 'authority to initiate litigation on behalf of the petitioner.' |display-authors=etal}}</ref> they filed this class action on behalf of all the detainees.
== Response == {{empty section|date=April 2015}}
