{{for2|the Romanian equivalent|[[zmeu]]|other Slavic counterparts|[[Slavic dragon]]}}

A '''''Zmei Gorynich''''' or '''''zmey''''' ({{lang-ru|[[:ru:Змей (мифология)|змей]]}}), in  ''[[Skazka]]'' (Russian folktales) and ''[[Bylina]]'' (epic poetry), is a [[dragon]] or serpent, or sometimes a human-like character with dragon-like traits.

Zmei Gorynych and [[Tugarin Zmeyevich]] are well-known ''zmei'', and appear as adversaries to the [[bogatyr]]i (heroes) [[Dobrynya Nikitich]] or [[Alyosha Popovich]].

==Etymology==
The word '''zmei''' in Russian is the masculine forms of ''zmeya'', a feminine noun, meaning "[[snake]]".{{sfnp|Bailey|Ivanova|1998|p=83}}

==General traits==

===Gender===
The dragon in Russian folk fiction may be female, in which case she is called ''zmeya''. The tendency is for the prose folktale versions to have male dragons, and the [[Bylina|byliny]] poetry to have the females.{{sfnp|Warner|2002|p=68}} This will affect the behavior of the dragons. For instance, only the male dragons will capture or captivate a princes or a maiden as a love interest.

===Multiheadedness===
The zmei is often depicted with [[Multi-headed animal|multiple heads]], and the number of heads may be 3, 6, 9, or 12.<ref name=kravchenko/>

A three-, six-, nine-, and twelve-headed dragon are defeated on successive nights by the hero of the tale "Ivan the Peasant's Son and the Little Man the Size of a Finger" ([[Alexander Afanasyev|Afanasyev]] #138). The twelve-headed one was hardest to kill, and although the hero beheaded it nearly completely, the last head had to be taken by six men provided to Ivan by the Tsar.<ref>"Ivan the Peasant's Son and the Little Man the Size of a Finger with Moustaches Seven Versts in Length", {{harvp|Curtin|1890|pp=37–46}}</ref>{{Refn|group="lower-alpha"|A three-, six-, and twelv-headed are killed in "Ivan Popyalov" (Иван Попялов, No. 135){{sfnp|Ralston|1880|pp=79–83}}}}

;Chudo-Iudo

In the variant "Ivan Bykovich (Ivan Buikovich)" (# 137),{{efn|Variant to "Ivan Popyalov" (#135), in Ralston's discussion, strictly speaking.}} an equivalent sets of these multi-headed creatures appear, but are not called ''zmei'', but a Chudo-Iudo (Chudo-Yudo). These are humanlike creatures, each one is riding a horse.{{Efn|The twelve-headed Chudo-Yudo rides a horse with twelve silver wings, which is gold-maned and tailed}} Even when decapitated, if the heads picked up the grow back on once a line is drawn on it with the dragon's fiery finger.<ref name=ivan-bykovich-ru>{{Wikisourcelang-inline|ru|Народные русские сказки (Афанасьев)/Иван Быкович|Иван Быкович}}</ref>{{sfnp|Ralston|1880|pp=83–86}} As is pointed out below, a ''zmei'' can take human-form, and in the variant "Storm-bogatyr, Ivan the Cow's Son" (#136), the multi-headed Chudo-Iudo are described as using the word ''zmei'' also.<ref name=burya-bogatyr-ru>{{Wikisourcelang-inline|ru|Народные русские сказки (Афанасьев)/Буря-богатырь Иван коровий сын|Буря-богатырь Иван коровий сын}}</ref>
<ref name=burya-bogatyr-levchin>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Levchin |first=Sergei |title=Blast-Bogatyr Ivan the Cow's Son|work=Russian Folktales from the Collection of A. Afanasyev: A Dual-Language Book |location=Mineola, New York |publisher=Dover |year=2014 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7XhpAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA153 |pages=153–}}</ref><ref name=burya-bogatyr-haney>{{harvp|Afanas'ev|Haney|2015}} {{plainlink|title=#136. Storm-bogatyr, Ivan the Cow's Son |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IQQbBwAAQBAJ&pg=PT401}}</ref>

===Other attributes===
The creature's appearance is not described in ''bylinas''.<ref>[http://2tq.ru/slovary/zmei.html Змей]. // Русский гуманитарный словарь. М., 2000.</ref> In more recent sources, the Russian zmei is described as being covered with either green<ref name=kravchenko/> or red<ref>[http://elib.bsu.by/bitstream/123456789/103289/1/%D0%9D%D0%B0%D0%B4%D0%B5%D0%B6%D0%B4%D0%B0%20%D0%9A%D0%BE%D0%BD%D0%BE%D0%B1%D0%B5%D0%B5%D0%B2%D0%B0%20%D0%A7%D0%B8%D1%81%D0%BB%D0%BE%D0%B2%D1%8B%D0%B5%20%D0%B8%20%D1%86%D0%B2%D0%B5%D1%82%D0%BE%D0%B2%D1%8B%D0%B5%20%D0%B0%D0%BA%D1%86%D0%B5%D0%BD%D1%82%D1%8B%20%D0%B2%20%D0%B1%D1%8B%D0%BB%D0%B8%D0%BD%D0%B5%20_%D0%94%D0%BE%D0%B1%D1%80%D1%8B%D0%BD%D1%8F%20%D0%B8%20%D0%B7%D0%BC%D0%B5%D0%B9_%20%D0%B8%20%D0%BC%D1%83%D0%BB%D1%8C%D1%82%D1%84%D0%B8%D0%BB%D1%8C%D0%BC%D0%B5%20_%D0%94%D0%BE%D0%B1%D1%80%D1%8B%D0%BD%D1%8F%20%D0%9D%D0%B8%D0%BA%D0%B8%D1%82%D0%B8%D1%87%20%D0%B8%20%D0%97%D0%BC%D0%B5%D0%B9%20%D0%93%D0%BE%D1%80%D1%8B%D0%BD%D1%8B%D1%87_.pdf Надежда Конобеева]</ref> scales, and having iron claws.<ref name=kravchenko/>

===Shapeshifting===
The ''zmei'' may turn into a handsome youth. In that form he enthralls the sister or wife of [[Ivan Tsarevich]] in different versions of {{illm|"The Milk of Wild Beasts"|fr|Le Lait de bête sauvage}} (Afanasyev #204, #205), as described below. In one of these (#204) the ''zmei'' also transforms into kitchen implements to avoid detection: he becomes a broom<!--besom-->, a sort of mop ([[:ru:Помело (метла)|помело]] ''pomelo'') and {{illm|oven fork|ru|ухват}}. But Ivan's obedient animals are able to detect the  presence of an intruder in these implements.{{sfnp|Afanas'ev|Haney|2015|loc=#204}}{{sfnp|Mizukami|2015|p=62}}

The ''zmei'' assumes the form of a golden goat in another tale ("The Crystal Mountain", Afanasyev #162).{{sfnp|Propp|1968|p=15}}

==In fairy tales==
[[Image:Змей Горыныч.jpg|thumb|''Zmey Gorynych'', by [[Viktor Vasnetsov]].]]
<!--[[Image:Zmei Gorinich (colour fixed).jpg|left|thumb|upright|''Zmey Gorynych'', by [[Viktor Vasnetsov]]-->
The ''zmei'' occurs in the literature of [[Russia]] and [[Ukraine]] in numerous wondertales (''{{linktext|skazki}}''{{Efn|Plural form of ''skazka'' {{linktext|ска́зка}}.}}) such as those in [[Alexander Afanasyev]]'s compilation ''[[Narodnye russkie skazki]]'',{{sfnp|Mizukami|2015|p=53}} and in the byliny (epic ballads), and rendered as "serpent" or "dragon". They may also appear as a character with "Zmei" or "Zmeyevich" (Zmeevich, etc.) in their proper name, and these may exhibit more human-like qualities, such as courting women.

===As fabulous beast===

The ''zmei'' slain by the [[bogatyr]] [[Dobrynya Nikitich]] in the bylina "Dobrynya and the Zmei" can be male or female. It may happen to be Zmei Gorynishche{{Efn|"Zmei Gorynchische" {{Lang|ru|Змей Горынчище}} may be the correct transcription. The [[Cyrillic]] form is the one given by Stangé-Zhirovova.}} ("Dragon, the Son of a Mountain").{{sfnp|Bailey|Ivanova|1998|p=81}}<ref>Version collected by [[Kirsha Danilov]]. Printed in: Evgenyeva, A. P. and {{illm|Boris Nikolaevich Putilov{{!}}Putilov|ru|Путилов, Борис Николаевич}} (1977), ''Ancient Russian poems'', p. 184, cited by Stangé-Zhirovova.</ref> This name is a variant form of "Zmei Gorynych" found in fairy tales.{{sfnp|Stangé-Zhirovova|1992|p=325}} Or it may be she-dragon without a name,<!--The patronymic Gorynych would not fit a female--> as in the byliny collected from [[Republic of Karelia|Karelian Russia]].<ref name="dobrynya&dragon-bailey">"Dobrynya and the Dragon" (English translation), in {{harvp|Bailey|Ivanova|1998|pp=84–97}}, after the version collected by [[Alexander Hilferding|A. F. Gilferding]] from [[Olonetsky District|Olonets]].</ref> The "Puchai River" was its haunt, but in the caves of the "Saracen Mountains" it raised its pups and kept hostages. It was capable of flight, and abducted a princess from [[Kiev]] by flying there.<ref name="dobrynya&dragon-bailey"/>

====Zmei Gorynych====
Zmei Gorynych (Russian: [[:ru:Змей Горыныч|Змей Горыныч]]) has decidedly dragon-like characteristics, such as having [[Multi-headed animal|multiple heads]] (from 3 to upwards of 12<ref name=mccullough/>), spitting fire, and being associated with a body of water.{{Efn|In contrast to [[Tugarin Zmeyevich]], etc., who have "anthropomorphic traits" ({{harvp|Bailey|Ivanova|1998|p=81}}).}}{{sfnp|Bailey|Ivanova|1998|p=81}}

However, "Zmei Gorynych" is not consistently beast-like, and he may appear in the guise of a human thoroughout in some works (See [[#Milk of Wild Beasts|§Milk of Wild Beasts]], [[#Dobrynya and Marinka|§Dobrynya and Marinka]]) below.<ref>Thus the Zmei Gorynych or Tugarin who feature as boyfriends of Marinka in ''Dobrynya and Marinka'' are noted as being "dragon-like figures" ({{harvp|Bailey|Ivanova|1998|p=99}})</ref>

===Anthropomorphism===
Sometimes there are "Sons of Zmei" (Zmeyevich being their [[patronymic]] surname) who are recognized as monsters with human qualities, or vice versa.<ref name=zoomorphic-anthropomorphic/>

====Tugarin Zmeyevich====
{{More|Tugarin}}
[[Tugarin Zmeyevich]] is one such with [[anthropomorphic]] characteristics.<ref name=zoomorphic-anthropomorphic>:{{sfnp|Bailey|Ivanova|1998|p=122}} "zoomorphic and anthropomorphic features are combined in him". Citing Propp (1958b), ''The Russian Heroic Epic'', pp. 206–24; {{illm|Boris Nikolaevich Putilov{{!}}Putilov|ru|Путилов, Борис Николаевич}} (1971b) "Сюжетная замкнутость и второй сюжетный план в славянском эпосе"<!--Siuzhetnaia zamknutost i vtori siuzhetnyi plan v slvianskom epose -->[Plot enclosure and plot background in the Slavic epic]", pp. 54–62.</ref> The half-human quality is borne out by the {{linktext|sobriquet}} ''zmei-[[bogatyr]]''<!--zmey-bogatyr--> (serpent-hero) given him,<ref name=1911-russlit/><ref name=alyosha-afanasyev&haney/> and from him being able to ride a horse like a human being in the folktale "[[Alyosha Popovich]]". Tugarin thus faces off against the bogatyr Alyosha, and is slain.<ref name=alyosha-afanasyev&haney>"Alyosha Popovich", {{harvp|Afanas'ev|Haney|2015|loc=#312}}</ref>

Tugarin is a great glutton, which is suggestive of a dragon; however Tugar still retains human form, even in the scene where he displays the extraordinary feat of devouring a whole swan, moving it from cheek to cheek, and spitting out the bones.{{sfnp|Bailey|Ivanova|1998|pp=122, 126}} Tugarin also has flying wings like a dragon,{{sfnp|Magnus|1916|p=168}}{{sfnp|Bailey|Ivanova|1998|p=122}} but some songs rationalize these a paper wings, a device attached to the horse.<ref name="alyosha&tugarin-bailey">"Alyosha Popovich, his Squire Yekim, and Tugarin" (English translation), in {{harvp|Bailey|Ivanova|1998|pp=124–129}}, after the version taken down by N. E. Onchukov from [[Arkhangelsk Oblast|Archangel Province]].</ref>

Tugarin is referred to as a pagan{{sfnp|Magnus|1916|p=168}} and he has been given overlays of a [[Tatar people|Tatar]] tyrant around the folkloric dragon.{{sfnp|Bailey|Ivanova|1998|p=122}} Some support the conjecture that Tugarin's name derives from "Tugar-Khan", or Tugor-Khan, of the Turkic [[Polovtsi|Polovets]],{{sfnp|Hapgood|1886|p=345}}{{Efn|Tugar-Khan appears as the ruler of the fictitious "Tugars" in the 1956 film ''[[Ilya Muromets (film)|Ilya Muromets]]''.<ref name=greenwood-soviet-films/>}} but this etymology has been discounted by later commentators.{{Refn|Discounted in favor of derivation that derives Tugar from ''tug'' meaning "grief".{{sfnp|Bailey|Ivanova|1998|pp=124–129}}}}<ref>{{citation|last= |first= |author-link=Sergei O. Prokofieff |title=The Spiritual Origins of Eastern Europe and the Future Mysteries of the Holy Grail |publisher=Temple Lodge Publishing |year=1993 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_y3nDzXvcB8C&pg=PA488 |page=488}} {{isbn|0904693554}}</ref>

====Milk of Wild Beasts====
The ''zmei'' also transforms into a handsome youth to seduce women (folktale {{illm|"The Milk of Wild Beasts"|fr|Le Lait de bête sauvage}},  #204, 205).{{sfnp|Propp|1968|p=15}} In one version, Zmei Gorynych seduces the sister of [[Ivan Tsarevich]]. She feigns illnesses and asks Ivan to perform the precarious task of retrieving the milk of the wolf, bear, and lioness. This plan fails. Later however, when Ivan is separted from his trusty pack of animals, zmei reveals his true nature and poises to devour him with his gaping mouth.{{sfnp|Afanas'ev|Haney|2015|loc=#204}}{{Efn|There is a later development where Ivan vanquishes a 12-headed dragon, but is beheaded by a water-carrier who sought to steal credit.}} In another version, Zmei Zmeyevich ("Serpent, Son of Serpent") and Ivan's adulterous wife play out a similar plot.{{sfnp|Afanas'ev|Haney|2015|loc=#205}}

===Other examples===
Zmei Gorynych or Tugarin Zmeyevich, in "Dobrynya and Marinka", play fleeting roles as the lover of Marinka the sorceress, and are instantly killed.<ref>{{harvp|Bailey|Ivanova|1998|p=99}}</ref><ref>{{harvp|Warner|2002|p=68}}. Zmei Gorynych.</ref><ref>{{harvp|Warner|2002}}, ""Dobrýnya the Dragon-Slayer, and Marína", p. 118, Marína (Marínushka Ignátievna) has Tugarin Dragon's Son as "her dear friend"</ref>

In some tales, this Zmei Zmeyevich is a [[tsar]].<ref name="marko&vasily">"Marko the Rich and Vasily the Luckless" or "Marko the Luckless" (Afanasyev #305)</ref>

==Other folktale literature==
===Eruslan Lazarevich===
{{more|Yeruslan Lazarevich{{!}}Eruslan Lazarevich}}
There is also the three-headed ''zmei'' defeated by [[Yeruslan Lazarevich|Eruslan Lazarevich]], hero of the story material found in [[popular print]] ([[Lubok|lubki]]).{{sfnp|Warner|2002|pp=67–68}}

===Saint George===
It was a ''zmei'', and not a ''drakon'' ({{lang-ru|драко́н}}) that was defeated by Saint George, or St. Egorii, as he was popularly known in Russia.{{sfnp|Warner|2002|p=19}} The saint appears as "Egorii the brave" ({{lang-ru|Егорий Храбрый}}, with the epithet "''chrabryii''") in religious verses.{{sfnp|Warner|2002|pp=67–68}}<ref name=lunk/> This can be seen in popular ''[[lubok]]'' prints of [[Saint George and the Dragon]]in Russia.<ref>{{harvp|Warner|2002}}, p. 68: See caption on the 19th century print photograph.</ref> The scene is also often depicted in [[Russian icons]].{{sfnp|Warner|2002|pp=67–68}}

